node.text:
What will you find in some of the ultra-wealthy’s portfolios that you won’t find in the typical financial plan? Multi-million dollar contemporary art.

According to publicly available data, contemporary art prices have outpaced the S&P 500 total return by 174% from 1995 to 2020. Also, contemporary art is one of the least correlated to the stock market of any major asset class according to a 2020 Citibank report.

When we say major, we mean it. Deloitte estimates that the global wealth held in art is around $1.7 trillion and projects it to grow $900 billion by 2026.

@masterworks.io allows you to invest a fraction of your overall portfolio in contemporary art by names like Banksy, Basquiat, Picasso, and more. Tap the link in our bio to check out our in depth review on @masterworks.io

node.text:
@themillennialmoneymentor breaking down why you shouldn’t just look at dividend yield
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
If you come across that has an abnormally high yield, you need to dig deeper and look into its payout ratio
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
This will tell you if the current rate that the company is paying dividends at is sustainable or not
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
This number will vary by industry, but generally you want to avoid ultra high payout ratio stocks because it means that the dividend is probably not sustainable and there may be other red flags to be aware of
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
In other words, it’s a yield trap
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
As always, do your own research and don’t look at any one number before investing in anything
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Make sure you SAVE this post for future reference!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
And follow @themillennialmoneymentor for more daily investing content 📈
